{"questionId":"17485","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A small cuboid box has a rectangular base of length <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"3x\">\n  <mn>3</mn>\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span> cm and width <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span> cm, where <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x > 0\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>&gt;</mo>\n  <mn>0</mn>\n</math></span>.&nbsp;The height is <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n</math></span> cm, where <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y > 0\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n  <mo>&gt;</mo>\n  <mn>0</mn>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/ff847104e6a7c9e4bf868993a1172ebfe7180522.png\"></p>\n<p>The&nbsp;sum of the length, width and height is <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"12\">\n  <mn>12</mn>\n</math></span> cm.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Write down an expression for <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y\"> <mi>y</mi> </math></span> in terms of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\"> <mi>x</mi> </math></span>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y = 12 - 4x\"> <mi>y</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>12</mn> <mo>−</mo> <mn>4</mn> <mi>x</mi> </math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em><em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;N1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17485","referenceCode":"19N.1.SL.TZ0.S_8a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Write down an expression for y in terms of x .","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.5—Integration introduction, areas between curve and x axis","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.7—The second derivative","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.8—Testing for max and min, optimisation. Points of inflexion"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}